# 📘 SOLID Principles in Java

A complete guide to SOLID Principles with definitions, benefits, examples, violations, corrections, and interview notes.

---

# What is SOLID?

SOLID is a set of five Object-Oriented Design Principles introduced by Robert C. Martin (Uncle Bob) to create software that is:

* Maintainable
* Flexible
* Scalable
* Reusable
* Easy to Test

---

# SOLID Overview

| Principle | Full Form                       | Key Idea                           |
| --------- | ------------------------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| S         | Single Responsibility Principle | One class → One responsibility     |
| O         | Open Closed Principle           | Extend without modifying           |
| L         | Liskov Substitution Principle   | Child should replace parent safely |
| I         | Interface Segregation Principle | Small focused interfaces           |
| D         | Dependency Inversion Principle  | Depend on abstractions             |

## Memory Trick

```text
S → One Job

O → Extend, Don't Modify

L → Child = Parent Behavior

I → Small Interfaces

D → Depend on Abstractions
```

